<div xmlns:perseus="http://www.perseus.org/meta/perseus.rdfs#" xmlns:dctype="http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/" xmlns:tufts="http://www.tufts.edu/" xmlns:alph="http://alpheios.net/namespaces/tei" class="alpheios-lex-text_container en">
    <div class="alpheios-lex-entry" lemma-id="n5622" body-key="α">
          <b><span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">κύκλος</span></b> , pl. <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">κύκλοι</span> and <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">κύκλα</span>: <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">ring, circle;</span>
          <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">δόλιος</span>, employed by hunters for
          capturing game, <i><span class="en">Od. 4.792</span></i>
          <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">; ἱερός</span>, the solemn circle of a
          tribunal, etc., <i><span class="en">Il. 18.504</span></i>;
            <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">wheel</span>, <i><span class="en">Il. 23.340</span></i>,
          pl., <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">τὰ κύκλα, Ε 722</span>, <i><span class="en">Il. 18.375</span></i>; of the <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">rings</span>
          on the outside of a shield, or the <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">layers</span> which, lying
          one above the other and gradually diminishing in size toward the boss,
          made up the whole disc, <i><span class="en">Il. 11.33</span></i>,
            <i><span class="en">Il. 20.280</span></i>.</div> <div class="alpheios-lex-footnotes en"> </div>
